   From: dfk@mcsun.UUCP  (Daniel Karrenberg)

   thorinn@DIKU.DK (Lars Henrik Mathiesen) writes:

   &gt;Since the only way to get from Internet to Janet seems to be through
	      ^^^^
-----------------------------------------------------^^^^^
   &gt;nsfnet-relay, and its only DNS name seems to be nsfnet-relay.ac.uk,
   &gt;which is not a legal Internet host name either, we might as well use
   &gt;the %-free form until such time as the Janet might decide to have
--------------------^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
   &gt;their gateways follow Internet rules on the Internet side.
	  ^^^^^^^^

   You contradict yourself.
If it must come to nitpicking: Actually not, because even if Janet had
only one gateway now, it might get more before it got the naming
matters straightened out.

   Assuming that there is only one route is almost always wrong and
   *always* shortsighted. In this case it is both.
Note the ``seems''. I just checked with the DNS server for UK; if we
assume Janet == ac.uk (I don't know if this is strictly true) then
nearly all hosts on Janet which are not themselves connected to the
Internet have a single MX record pointing to nsfnet-relay.ac.uk. (The
single exception is buckingham.ac.uk which also MX'es mcsun.eu.net).

Of course, many of these hosts may be reachable through UUCP, EAN,
EARN, BITNET or other paths, but _there_is_no_mechanism_ that allows
such routes to be found from the domain name of the hosts. In that
sense, it is true that the only gateway from the Internet to Janet is
nsfnet-relay.ac.uk.

